### Indexers in C#

Indexers allow objects to be indexed like arrays using the `[]` notation.

### Declaring Indexers

```csharp
public class SampleCollection<T>
{
    private T[] arr = new T[100];

    // Indexer declaration
    public T this[int index]
    {
        get => arr[index];
        set => arr[index] = value;
    }
}

// Usage
var collection = new SampleCollection<string>();
collection[0] = "Hello";
Console.WriteLine(collection[0]);  // "Hello"
```

### Indexer with Multiple Parameters

```csharp
public class Matrix
{
    private int[,] data;

    public Matrix(int rows, int cols)
    {
        data = new int[rows, cols];
    }

    // 2D indexer
    public int this[int row, int col]
    {
        get => data[row, col];
        set => data[row, col] = value;
    }
}

var matrix = new Matrix(3, 3);
matrix[0, 0] = 10;
Console.WriteLine(matrix[0, 0]);  // 10
```

### Indexer with Non-Int Keys

```csharp
public class HttpCookie
{
    private Dictionary<string, string> cookies = new();

    public string this[string key]
    {
        get => cookies.TryGetValue(key, out var value) ? value : string.Empty;
        set => cookies[key] = value;
    }

    public DateTime this[string key, bool expired]
    {
        get => expired ? DateTime.MinValue : DateTime.Now;
    }
}

var cookie = new HttpCookie();
cookie["session"] = "abc123";
Console.WriteLine(cookie["session"]);  // "abc123"
```

### Read-Only and Write-Only Indexers

```csharp
public class ReadOnlyCollection<T>
{
    private readonly T[] items;

    public ReadOnlyCollection(T[] items) => this.items = items;

    // Read-only indexer
    public T this[int index] => items[index];
}
```

### Indexer Overloading

```csharp
public class Translations
{
    private Dictionary<string, string> enToFr = new();

    public string this[string word]  // String index
    {
        get => enToFr.TryGetValue(word, out var t) ? t : "";
        set => enToFr[word] = value;
    }

    public string this[int index]    // Int index (overloaded)
    {
        get => enToFr.ElementAt(index).Value;
    }
}
```

### Indexers in Interfaces

```csharp
public interface IStringTable
{
    string this[string key] { get; set; }
}

public class StringTable : IStringTable
{
    private Dictionary<string, string> data = new();
    public string this[string key]
    {
        get => data[key];
        set => data[key] = value;
    }
}
```

### Indexer vs Property

| Aspect | Indexer | Property |
|--------|---------|----------|
| Access syntax | `obj[index]` | `obj.Name` |
| Parameters | Required (one or more) | None |
| Name | `this` | User-defined name |
| Overloading | Multiple overloads possible | One per name |
| Static | Cannot be static | Can be static |

> **Key Point:** Indexers let you define custom indexing behavior for your classes. They are declared using `this` keyword with parameters. Indexers can have multiple parameters and can be overloaded. Common uses: collection wrappers, data structures, string-keyed access.

### Virtual Indexers

```csharp
public virtual string this[int index] { get; set; }
```

### Indexer with Enum Key

```csharp
public enum Field { Name, Age, Email }

public class Record
{
    public string this[Field field] => field switch
    {
        Field.Name => Name,
        Field.Age => Age.ToString(),
        Field.Email => Email,
        _ => ""
    };
}

